   (Message) ROOT CAUSE: `program.c:22` – In the recoverable‑error path of
   `load_blob` the code executes `free(b->name);` and then returns the `blob_t`.
   The pointer stored in `b->name` is thus freed, but the surrounding `blob_t`
   structure is still handed to the caller and later passed to `destroy_blob`,
   which again calls `free(b->name)`. Because the pointer is now dangling, the
   second free triggers AddressSanitizer’s double‑free detector, causing the
   observed crash. This happens because the function both allocates and
   unconditionally frees the same owned buffer on an error path, violating the
   single‑ownership invariant that the caller expects the destructor to clean up
   all allocated resources.
   
   LOCAL FIX: Remove the premature free of `b->name` on the error path so that
   the destructor remains the sole owner of the allocated memory. The change can
   be expressed as a diff:
   
   ```
   @@ -22,1 +22,1 @@
   -        free(b->name);      /* release the name on the recoverable error path */
   +        /* release the name on the recoverable error path */
   +        /* intentionally skip freeing – ownership stays with destroy_blob */
   ```
   
   After this edit the recovered blob is returned with its `name` pointer still
   valid, and `destroy_blob` will free it exactly once, eliminating the
   double‑free.
   
   GLOBAL FIX: Redesign the API so that resource ownership is unambiguous and
   cannot be double‑released. A robust approach is to give `load_blob` a single
   responsibility: allocate and partially initialise the blob but never free any
   of its fields. All deallocation should be performed exclusively by
   `destroy_blob`. To enforce this, the implementation could return error codes
   instead of using a recoverable‑error‑path that frees memory, or employ a
   “cleanup‑on‑exit” label that jumps to a common exit point where only
   `destroy_blob` executes the frees. By centralising the free operation in one
   function and ensuring that no other code interferes with the owned pointers,
   the class of double‑free bugs caused by premature releases is prevented. This
   structural change makes the ownership discipline explicit and guarantees that
   each allocated resource is freed exactly once.
